  "prompt": "Why did oil prices fall again in 2015?",
  "response": "Oil prices fell again in 2015 due to a combination of factors that created an oversupply in the market and reduced demand. Key reasons for the decline in oil prices include:\n\n1. **Increased Production**: There was an increase in oil production from non-OPEC countries, particularly the United States, which saw significant growth in shale oil output. Advances in hydraulic fracturing (fracking) technology allowed for higher production rates.\n\n2. **OPEC's Decision**: OPEC (Organization of the Petroleum Exporting Countries), led by Saudi Arabia, decided not to cut production despite the falling prices. This decision was partly aimed at maintaining market share and putting pressure on high-cost producers, but it contributed to the oversupply problem.\n\n3. **Weak Global Demand**: Global demand for oil was weaker than expected, partly due to slower economic growth in major economies such as China and Europe. This lower demand further exacerbated the imbalance between supply and demand.\n\n4. **Strong US Dollar**: The strengthening of the US dollar during this period made crude oil (priced in dollars) more expensive for customers using other currencies, leading to decreased demand.\n\n5. **Geopolitical Factors**: Several geopolitical factors also influenced market sentiment and production levels, including conflicts in oil-producing regions, but overall they contributed to the complexity of the situation rather than promoting price increases.\n\nThese factors, combined with market dynamics and investor sentiment, led to a significant drop in oil prices throughout 2015.",
